\section{Simulation}

To demonstrate the validity of the proposed model, submicron SiC MESFETs of various $L_g$ were chosen and the detail of which is given in Table \ref{Tab:1}. A MATLAB simulator was developed wherein the respective model equations were used \cite{Quanjun2008,Dobes2004,Manohar2002,McNallay2001,Angelov1999,Yuk2008,Robert1999,McCamant1990,Statz1987,Curtice1985}. Optimization of different variables of a model has been carried out using Particle Swarm Optimization (PSO) technique and a brief of which is as under \cite{Memon2013,Mousa2012}.

PSO was initialized with random position and velocity for the parameters which were to be optimized. Positions were initialized within a boundary defined by $x_{max}$ and $x_{min}$ and the velocity was initialized somewhere between 0 to $v_{max}$, where $v_{max}$ is given by:
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:12}
v_{max}=\frac{x_{max}-x_{min}}{2}~.
\end{equation}
For an $n$-dimensional problem with $m$ number of particles and for $k^{th}$ iteration, the positions were represented by:
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:13}
X^k=
\begin{bmatrix}
x_{11}^k & x_{12}^k & \hdots & x_{1j}^k & \hdots & x_{1n}^k \\
x_{21}^k & x_{22}^k & \hdots & x_{2j}^k & \hdots & x_{2n}^k \\
\vdots   & \vdots   & \ddots & \vdots   & \vdots & \vdots   \\
x_{i1}^k & x_{i2}^k & \hdots & x_{ij}^k & \hdots & x_{in}^k \\
\vdots   & \vdots   & \hdots & \vdots   & \ddots & \vdots   \\
x_{m1}^k & x_{m2}^k & \hdots & x_{mj}^k & \hdots & x_{mn}^k
\end{bmatrix}
\end{equation}
where $m$ is swarm size and $n$ is swarm dimension. The associated velocities of these particles were represented as:
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:14}
V^k=
\begin{bmatrix}
v_{11}^k & v_{12}^k & \hdots & v_{1j}^k & \hdots & v_{1n}^k \\
v_{21}^k & v_{22}^k & \hdots & v_{2j}^k & \hdots & v_{2n}^k \\
\vdots   & \vdots   & \ddots & \vdots   & \vdots & \vdots   \\
v_{i1}^k & v_{i2}^k & \hdots & v_{ij}^k & \hdots & v_{in}^k \\
\vdots   & \vdots   & \hdots & \vdots   & \ddots & \vdots   \\
v_{m1}^k & v_{m2}^k & \hdots & v_{mj}^k & \hdots & v_{mn}^k
\end{bmatrix}
\end{equation}
Modification of the particle position was realized by using the current position and the velocity information as defined by:
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:15}
X^{k+1}=V^{k+1}+X^k~,
\end{equation}
where $X^{k+1}$ was the modified position and $V^{k+1}$ was the modified velocity. The velocity of a particle was calculated by the equation:
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:16}
v_{ij}^{k+1}=w_{ij} v_{ij}^k+v_{p\mathrm{best}}+v_{g\mathrm{best}}~,
\end{equation}
where the term $w_{ij} v_{ij}^k$ was called inertia and it specified the velocity which was retained from the previous step. The $2^{\text{nd}}$ term $v_{p\mathrm{best}}$ of \eqref{Eq:16} was given by:
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:17}
v_{p\mathrm{best}}=c_1\times \Phi_1\times ({p_{\mathrm{best}}}_{ij}^k-x_{ij}^k)~.
\end{equation}
The $3^{\text{rd}}$ term $v_{g\mathrm{best}}$ of \eqref{Eq:16} represented global velocity referred to as social influence which was defined by:
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:18}
v_{g\mathrm{best}}=c_2\times \Phi_2\times (g_{\mathrm{best}}-x_{ij}^k )~.
\end{equation}
In \eqref{Eq:16} to \eqref{Eq:18} $x_{ij}^k$ represented current position of a particle at $k^{th}$ iteration, $v_{ij}^k$ current velocity of a particle, $v_{ij}^{k+1}$ modified velocity, $\Phi_1$  and $\Phi_2$ random numbers between 0 and 1, ${p_{\mathrm{best}}}_{ij}^k$ personal best, $g_{\mathrm{best}}$ global best and $w_{ij}$ weighting factor of the velocity of a particle at position $x_{ij}$.

Further, $c_1$ was a cognitive parameter and represented individual best success so far whilst $c_2$ was a social parameter and neighbor best success so far. Increasing $c_1$ encourages each particle to move towards its own $p_{\mathrm{best}}$ while increasing $c_2$ encourages exploration of $g_{\mathrm{best}}$. In our simulation the values of $c_1$ and $c_2$ were changed iteratively by using following expression:
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:19}
c_1=c_{1\mathrm{max}}+\frac{c_{1\mathrm{max}}-c_{1\mathrm{min}}}{\text{max.iter}} \text{(max.iter}-k)~.
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:20}
c_2=c_{2\mathrm{max}}+\frac{c_{2\mathrm{max}}-c_{2\mathrm{min}}}{\text{max.iter}} (\text{max.iter}-k)~.
\end{equation}
The convergence of PSO was achieved by devising an objective function given by:
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:21}
\varepsilon=\sqrt{\sum_{Q=1}^N \left\{\sum_{P=1}^M\left( I_{ds(\mathrm{exp})}^{P,Q}-I_{ds(\mathrm{sim})}^{P,Q}\right)^2
\Bigg/
\sum_{P=1}^M I_{ds(\mathrm{exp})}^{P,Q}
\right\}}~.
\end{equation}
And the root mean square error (RMSE) between the simulated and the experimental data was assessed by using:
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:22}
\textrm{RMSE}=\sqrt{\frac{1}{M} \sum_{P=1}^M\left( I_{ds(\mathrm{exp})}^P-I_{ds(\mathrm{sim})}^P\right)^2}~.
\end{equation}
In \eqref{Eq:21} $P$ represents steps in $V_{ds}$ starting from zero to its maximum biasing value given by $M$, whereas $Q$ represents number of steps in $V_{gs}$  with its highest number given by $N$. To avoid discontinuity, which may be caused by the denominator of the square term of \eqref{Eq:9}, optimization variables' bounds were defined to ensure the convergence and the same was observed routinely.

Following steps were used in the implementation of PSO algorithm:
\begin{enumerate}[topsep=0pt,itemsep=0.5ex,partopsep=1ex,parsep=1ex]
\item{define swarm dimension and size with initialized position and velocity;}
\item{define objective function for error estimation;}
\item{update each particle's position using \eqref{Eq:15};}
\item{obtain personal best, $p_{\mathrm{best}}$ (according to the particle's previous best positions) with the help of defined objective function;}
\item{obtain global best, $g_{\mathrm{best}}$;}
\item{update velocity based on previous best and global best positions through \eqref{Eq:16};}
\item{terminate if stopping criteria are satisfied, otherwise go to step 3.}
\end{enumerate}

Fig. \ref{Fig:2} shows experimental and simulated $I-V$ characteristics of four SiC MESFETs having submicron gate lengths but of varying geometry and doping density as given in Table 1. Simulation was carried out using \eqref{Eq:9} whereas, the variables of the equation were optimized using PSO algorithm discussed hitherto. The values of different variables of \eqref{Eq:9} which were achieved repeatedly after several executions of PSO are listed in Table \ref{Tab:2}.

Fig. \ref{Fig:3} shows simulated and experimental $g_d$ characteristics for the devices under discussion. Simulation was carried out by using \eqref{Eq:10} and the respective device data is listed in Table \ref{Tab:2}. The plots show that the experimental data is of scattered nature but it follow a definite pattern in which it exhibit a rapid decline in $g_d$ magnitude and subsequently it attain a saturation value.

Fig.~\ref{Fig:4} shows dependence of $g_m$ on $V_{ds}$ and $V_{gs}$ for submicron SiC MESFETs. The figure  shows that each device, dependent upon its channel conditions and Schottky barrier quality, offers a unique response. It is pertinent to mention that the simulated $g_m$ characteristics of Fig. \ref{Fig:4} are attained by employing \eqref{Eq:11} which exhibited a good agreement to the experimental data for entire $V_{gs}$ biasing.

\section{Discussion}

Examination of Fig. \ref{Fig:2} clearly reveals that the proposed model offers a reasonable accuracy both in the linear as well as in the saturation region of operation for submicron SiC MESFETs. It also demonstrates that \eqref{Eq:9} is versatile enough to simulate, without compromising on accuracy, devices having different physical dimensions (Table \ref{Tab:1}).  Further a careful investigation of Fig. \ref{Fig:2} showed that the profile of $I_{ds}(V_{ds}, V_{gs})$ characteristics differs from device to device. Fig. \ref{Fig:2}(a) exhibits a typical behavior of a short channel device and for such devices the observed $V_T$ conforms well to the value evaluated from \eqref{Eq:8}. On the other hand, all the remaining devices exhibited a non-ideal response (shift in $V_T$) most probably due to the presence of interface states at the Schottky barrier gate \cite{Ahmed1995}. A good agreement between simulated and experimental characteristics showed that \eqref{Eq:9} addresses adequately the device physical parameters and thus can be used for a wider range of $I-V$ characteristics simulation involving SiC MESFETs.

