To compare the performance of \eqref{Eq:9} with other models commonly used for MESFET simulation a comprehensive  comparative study was carried out. Table 3 shows RMS error values at different $V_{gs}$ biasing evaluated using \eqref{Eq:22} for $L_g=0.7~\mu$m device. The last column of the table also lists the average RMS error by which a model can be compared with its counterparts. From data of Table \ref{Tab:3}, it is evident that the proposed model for $L_g=0.7~\mu$m device offers 21.17~\% improved performance compared to the $2^{\text{nd}}$ best observed model, i.e., McNallay model \cite{McNallay2001}.

A similar comparison was also carried out for devices having $L_g=0.6, 0.5, 0.4~\mu$m and the results are shown in Table \ref{Tab:4}, \ref{Tab:5} and \ref{Tab:6} respectively. Table \ref{Tab:4} shows that for $L_g=0.6~\mu$m device, the proposed model is 24.77~\% better than the $2^{\text{nd}}$ best observed model which in this case is the Curtice Cubic model \cite{Curtice1985}. The comparative analysis of Table \ref{Tab:4} was for pulsed $I-V$ characteristics which were chosen in order to observe the model performance for pulsed input. The data demonstrated that the proposed model has once again out performed  with good margin the other models listed in the table.

Table \ref{Tab:5} shows that for $L_g=0.5~\mu$m device, the proposed model offers 17.71~\% improved performance compared to the next best observed model which in this case is the Angelov model \cite{Angelov1999}.

