Table \ref{Tab:6} provides error data for $L_g=0.4~\mu$m SiC MESFET. The characteristics of this device were the most difficult  one to simulate because, the device at higher biasing exhibited self-regulating break down as evident from the plot. A good observed accuracy in simulated characteristics as seen in Fig. \ref{Fig:2}(d) demonstrates that the proposed model is a quite comprehensive one and takes into account $2^{\text{nd}}$ order  effects which can influence the device behavior.

Table \ref{Tab:6} data clearly shows that the error margin for this device is higher than all previously reported cases. However, the proposed model has once again shown better performance relative to other models. The next best observed model in this case was the Angelov model but, the proposed model performance in aggregate was 7.35~\% better than the Angelov model.

In general, one can say that \eqref{Eq:9} can be employed to simulate both static as well as pulsed $I-V$ characteristics of SiC MESFETs with a high degree of accuracy, especially for those devices which are designed for microwave power applications. Further, \eqref{Eq:9} is based on fundamental square law which governs the channel characteristics of a device as a function of its geometrical parameters.

Output conductance $(g_d)$ of the devices under discussion exhibits an exponential decay as a function of $V_{ds}$ as evident from Fig. \ref{Fig:3}. The simulation which was carried out using \eqref{Eq:10} complies well with the experimental data. The point at which $g_d$ saturates is the same where $I_{ds}$ saturates for a given $V_{gs}$. Examination of Fig. \ref{Fig:3}(a) shows that $g_d$ saturates at $V_{ds}\sim~7$~V whereas, this is $\sim$~17 V for the device of Fig.~\ref{Fig:3}(d). Saturation at relatively higher $V_{ds}$ values is primarily associated with high source resistance and the value of $\alpha$ in \eqref{Eq:10} simulates this effect. From Table \ref{Tab:1}, $\alpha=0.3402$ for the device of Fig. \ref{Fig:3}(a) and $\alpha=0.1277$ for the device of Fig. \ref{Fig:3}(d). A relatively high value of $\alpha$ will then mean that the device $g_d$ will saturates quickly thus, indicating that the device offers low source resistance.

